          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">EU agrees with sanctions on Russia</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/eu-16th-sanctions-package-russia.png" alt="EU approves the 16th sanctions package against Russia" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">EU approves the 16th sanctions package against Russia. Credits: United24 media</p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
         
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">The EU has approved its <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-20-02-2025-h2-2-16th-sanction-package-against-russia?source=website" target="_blank">16th sanctions package against Russia</a>, banning aluminum imports and imposing export restrictions ahead of the three-year mark of Russia’s invasion of Ukraine. The sanctions target shadow fleet vessels, chemicals, chrome, and precision machine tools while prohibiting servicing for Russian oil and gas refineries. A certain threshold of imports would be allowed before a complete ban kicks in.</p>

          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Despite initial concerns from Greece, the EU agreed to halt imports of Russian aluminum. However, the sanctions package does not include a complete ban on Russian liquefied natural gas (LNG) as EU leaders await trade negotiations with Trump’s administration. This approach reflects the EU’s continued efforts to weaken Russia’s economy while maintaining strategic flexibility on energy imports. </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">The sanctions would restrict the use of 11 ports and airports in Russia that the EU considers are being used to help Moscow bypass an oil market value cap. As Brussels considers its next moves against Moscow, future policies may depend on securing alternative LNG sources, particularly from the US. On Wednesday, many EU leaders, including Norway and Canada, had an emergency summit on Ukraine to discuss these issues. </p>
        </mj-text>
