          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Hamas holds its word</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;"><strong>Summary: Hamas will hand over the remaining hostages and release six living hostages on Saturday ahead of talks on the second phase of the ceasefire agreement.</strong></p>

          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Hamas has <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-20-02-2025-h3-3-handover-bodies-of-four-hostages?source=website" target="_blank">handed over the bodies of four hostages</a>, including Shiri Bibas and her two young children, who were abducted during the October 7, 2023 attack. Hamas alleges that the three were killed in Israeli bombardment. The bodies were first transferred to the Red Cross and then to the Israeli Military inside Gaza. A forensic examination of the bodies will be conducted at Abu Kabir Institute of Forensic Medicine in Tel Aviv. </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Hamas will release six living hostages on Saturday, including Avera Mengistu and Hisham al-Sayed, alongside four others taken on October 7. In exchange, Israel will release all Palestinian women and minors arrested since last October and allow some construction equipment into Gaza. Under the first phase, Hamas agreed to release 33 hostages, and Israel decided to release 1,900 Palestinian prisoners.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Talks on a second-phase agreement, which potentially leads to the release of remaining hostages and a permanent ceasefire, have yet to begin, as Hamas demands an Israeli withdrawal from Gaza and rejects disarmament. Israel insists Hamas must not stay in power. The Palestinian Authority also agrees with Israel on the subject of Hamas remaining in power.</p>
        </mj-text>
    </mj-section>
